Ries: What I've heard from others is that Pentaho is too broken to deploy and use right now.. the implementation and documentation are confusing. I haven't tried it myself (yet), but I wouldn't be surprised. Ries: From the look of their web pages, and the look of the JFree web site, it appears they're doing massive consolidation and refactoring right now, so I'd be surprised if what you download there is useable at the moment. Well, not JFreeChart exactly.. JFreeReport.. it's becoming part of Pentaho. And, right now I think Pentaho is a mess. http://www.pentaho.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=124&Itemid=238 Ries: You just need good docs, and then it's easy. Ries: Java/JSP/Tomcat is slightly faster than PHP/Apache Ries: The people who say Java is slow are the people who stand to gain the most from Java being slow, and from people beginning to believe that Java is slow. Ries: But, there have been some pretty fair benchmark tests that found PHP/Apache to be slightly slower than Tomcat/JSP/Java.. and Tomcat/Java (no JSP). Ries: It ends up being very hard to compare them fairly since both sets of technologies are broad, with lots of features each, and since the features don't exactly correspond, it is hard to write a fair test for each feature you wish to compare, and if you don't compare them all then you don't have the full picture. Ries: It was with an accelerator.. but as usual the details are somewhat sketchy. I wish someone would put together a team dedicated to getting to the bottom of this question in as fair and open a manner as possible. Ries: It really comes down to a couple of main things: which web server is faster, Apache or Tomcat? Which web scripting language is faster, PHP or JSP? But, each of those isn't one big feature to compare, it's a large set of features to compare. jbalint: Yes, but it's worse than that since no single webapp can be called "average", nor representitive of what each of us is trying to write. jbalint: So, instead, you have to benchmark zillions of individual features.. and on like 5 different operating systems each.. yassine: Hi yassine. Things are good, just been unusually busy. wltjr: That's for sure! Like JRockit or Excelsior JET for example! jbalint: Nah.. that's not true. There are some JVMs out there that do a better job of some things than Sun's JVM, and people do use them. Also, different traffic loads would need to be tested.. so it's a multi-dimensional graph for each feature that would need to be compared. Sun is still learning their lesson over Linux. wltjr: PHP is also multithreaded, but how well it does that has a lot to do with which Apache version you run it through. wltjr: I find it funny that most PHP developers use Apache 1.3, which only has a multi-process model, not a multi-thread model. wltjr: I believe new versions of PHP can run threaded code. wltjr: well, lots of PHP developers use 1.3 because for a long time PHP did not support Apache 2.0 or higher. People who I know who used PHP for a significant amount of time ended up dropping it for Java/JSP/servlets eventually in most cases, saying that the PHP language itself was really shaky and not what it needed to be. Plus, Java is a much more full featured programming language, and is the most widely used professional programming language today. wltjr: You're going to be in the SF bay area? wltjr: Ahh. I'm going to be busy next week, all except for Friday. I don't know about this weekend though. I might have some time. wltjr: When do you fly home? wltjr: BTW: Lyken is out here now too. :) wltjr: Developers who like coding in C have a major stylistic conflict with anything orderly like Java, so I don't expect them to like it. hi swente. :) Well, when people do surveys to find out what languages businesses are using to develop their products, that's what I try to see. That does include lots of OSS since lots of OSS does start out or end up in a company. Lots of people are.. for no good reason. But, that hasn't stopped zillions of OSS Java projects from springing up all over. It could be more, but.. Eventually there will be a completely OSS (and good) JVM, so then I wonder what OSS folks will think of Java at that point. That will happen eventually. I just wonder if someone else won't donate their clean-room JVM before that happens. I was hoping for Excelsior JET, but they just licensed Java from Sun so I think it's not a clean-room impl anymore. :( Open source hardware is a failed concept as far as I can tell. Open source software, though, isn't. heh We can... nachos.

hey guys anyone interested in developing a "generic" HTML5 GUI framework? well, here's the drill a few months ago i realized that the "world of programming" is headed towards disaster and what i mean is that there's not one single framework out there that one can rely upon anymore Qt is all but jettisoned, .NET is only officially implemented on windows, Java is very unlikely to ever get on android and iOS, etc so nowadays what exactly is a programmer supposed to do if he wants to develop an cross-platform app with some chances for the underlying framework to still be supported in a couple of years from now by HTML5 GUI framework i mean a sockets-based HTML5 "page" on which an app can programatically add buttons/text/widgets/you-name-it (via the local loop) so you open this "page" in a [stripped-down] browser (i.e. it can be with no chrome), and then the "page" listens to commands on a socket so the app you'd write would look like:  <program_in_whatever_language_with_a_socket_interface> <local_loop> <HTML5_GUI_page> i mean, i just realized that i can't start writing a program anymore because you really can't tell what development framework will still be around in a couple of years from now how much should be on the backend and how much in JS on the browser is a matter of design decision that i dind't really think very much about but it shouldn't matter to the user, because the user should only use some UI classes and he shouldn't care how their implementation is split between the backend and the browser if you put more "intelligence" in the browser, the UI classes would be easier to implement in multiple languages (i guess) my point is: i think this is the future of programming for anything that doesn't require very high I/O speed on the UI, and i was wondering how could i get this started anyone here has any experience with starting an open source project? 92b4371d9cd697c4659a3b0c41970c78 -> yes, sure, but the thing is i'd like to start this thing right, because there's not much "prototypiong" to do here, not much research involved, it's just to define the framweork properly and then implement it right basically, i might start doing it alone, but i'd rather like to make a multi-contributor project out of this 2cdd7064b290132617248dbfd85f740e -> which ones are you talking about (a couple of examples so i understand what you mean) yeah, probably i should try that first... i think this is the next holly grail you have standards for programming for ages now, but no standards were available for UIs now suh standards seem to come to age so basically this will close the circle (i mean having a standard UI language) how i ran into this: i wanted to write a "skype killer" and i ran in two problems: 1) i always counted on writing it in Qt once i finish with the "research" stage and now Qt is going no-one-knows-where 2) IPv6 is going no-one-knows-where i didn't think of making something profitable i just wanted an open alternative so that people can have a choice, and this would have put some real pressure on skype to behave 3e65db05e37f34bd21c82600a0356298 -> thanks for taking over, i didn't want to be sarcastic :-) dude, if the profit you're talking about s in the billions, IN A F* UP WORLD AS IS TODAY WHERE YOU CAN'T COUNT ON ANYTHING ABYMORE, selling for $8b the best biz plan ever :-) WebRTC -> no checking it out now 3e65db05e37f34bd21c82600a0356298 -> i'll check it out (WebRTC) 0de37da1d654c10aed33d7b7347b8e3b http://p2pos.com i'll have to see what it's about first, i mean, if it is what i'm thinking of (standradized cross-platform GUI enabler) i don't really want skype in a browser, no no no i'm on a totally different path with what i was talking about i mean i want to have something on the lines of Borland builder/Qt Creator/etc, but it should use a simple HTML5 renderer for all UI instead of platform specific stuff checking (Construct 2) .... okay, i added hat to the to read list but i hope i managed to make myself clear enough: at the end of the day i want to be able to write a C++ program whose (probably only) eveny will be "socket data received" and whose (probably only) output will be "write to socket", and this program should rely on a my HTML5 GUI "page" to do all the user interaction yes, but maybe the C will also be split 92b4371d9cd697c4659a3b0c41970c78, i'll tell you why i'd like to not work alone on this: i have a very nasty experience with my "skype killer" in the sense that i simply diregarded some basic issues, i simply DIDN'T SEE THEM until after i spent a freakin' year working on it i mean, i'd really value some brainstorming both before starting such a project, and in the course of its actual development i sort of lost confidence in my abilities to spot all the potential problems that may lie ahead and it's a lot of work we're talking about... yup was hpoing to find someone to say "kewl, let's do it!" here :-) :D well, laterz all, and thanks just came back to show you guys this: http://www.webtoolkit.eu (see e.g. http://www.webtoolkit.eu/wt/examples/ )

out of curiosity if I do <a>foo<span>bar</a>baz</span> what happens? <!DOCTYPE html>, so yes i.e., do both bar and baz get styled with the span and foo and bar get the link? damn oh well well, I need the <a> to stay an <a> basically, I'm trying to refactor this code2html utility I'm writing so I get syntax highlighting as regions and link objects also as regions I'm not sure I care about partially overlapping syntax highlighting/linkificaiton since that would be somebody's bug but links can be entirely within sytanx regions (i.e., an http in a comment) or syntax regions can be entirely within links (i.e., quallified namespaces) I'm not sure I have a case where a link and syntax region partially overlap... I've noticed s/span/b/g changes the resulting dom to do the logically right thing for my use case I was just wondering if the corner cases would have worked even if I didn't look for them

yes? per spec? the doctype doesn't affect this i think http://software.hixie.ch/utilities/js/live-dom-viewer/?%20%3Ca%3Efoo%3Cspan%3Ebar%3C%2Fa%3Ebaz%3C%2Fspan%3E test it in webkit or firefox, they implement the spec the resulting document has one <span> and it contains just "bar" note that <a> is particularly special here and you'll get different results if you replace it with <b>, for example also different results if you replace the <span> with <div>, say oh right, <a>'s specialness is when you nest <a>s you'll get different results if you change <a> to <Span> and <Span> to <div>? anyway my point is just that that general pattern can give various results depending on the element in question what's the context of your question? ah yeah you definitely don't want to rely on weird parsing behaviours here they're invalid for a reason :-) the best bet when doing docs with two overlapping ranges is to wrap one set of ranges normally, and then do the second set at the fine-grained level by rewrapping just the text nodes for the second set e.g. if you have  hel(lo[ pret)ty wor]ld you'd do "hel<span>lo pret</span> world" first and then (using <b>s for the sake of clarity: "hel<span>lo<b> pret</b></span><b> wor</b>ld" second if you have more than two sets of ranges, you're best off just dealing with ranges individually, as in: "hel<span class="a">lo</span><span class="a b"> pret</span><span class="b"> wor</span>ld" hth

No. Depends on a lot of things. Most people want to index most of their tables. Indexes are for searching within the table. If this table is to dump info, then you may not want the extra overhead of an index. Do you ever want to get data out of the table? Or run UPDATEs? Updates or deletes. Indexes will help UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT queries. Sometimes INSERTs. They speed up looking for records. However, indexes also slow down the table because if you insert or modify data, the index has to be updated too. Now you made me forget what I was going to Google... darn you. b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: not everyone on the TAG has a clear view of the harbor er, meant that comment for b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9 but you guys know what I meant I don't think anyone suggested switching browser *behavior* for XHTML/HTML based on anything other than MIME type, but there was an argument that it's ok if some document that in some sense "is" XHTML as text/html, if processing as HTML is what you want I think, anyway minutes are muddled well, the spec introduces this distinction somewhat, when it says, "XML documents that use elements or attributes from the HTML namespace and that are served over the wire (e.g. by HTTP) must be sent using an XML MIME type such as application/xml or application/xhtml+xml and must not be served as text/html." so that raises the question whether a document "is" an XML document - particularly tricky in light of polyglot document support the spec already says separately that anything sent as text/html will be treated as HTML I'm not sure I even know what that paragraph means I think the MIME type registrations included in the document might already say that (maybe not as to XML documents served as text/xml or application/xml instead of application/xhtml+xml) but yeah, anything that doesn't form to the HTML syntax must not be served as text/html anything that conforms to the XML syntax either is also valid HTML (in which case you can in fact send it as text/html), or it's not, in which case it's already invalid the sentence I cited superficially seems to forbid serving polyglot documents as text/html, which is inconsistent with the rest of the spec I don't think it even means to prohibit that it seems like it assumes there's some platonic sense in which something is either an HTML document or an XML document (based on author's intent? I dunno) and thus can't really be checked it sort of seems like it's saying "don't serve XHTML as HTML unless you know it's not really going to get processed as XML" that would be a fine thing to say

fwiw, I think the above paragraph is not necessary, or at least should be worded differently it should just say that documents in the HTML namespace served with an XML mime type must conform to the XML (XHTML) syntax and that documents served as text/html must conform to the HTML syntax and leave it at that yeah I don't think it's necessary for it to have that prohibition nor anything similar yeah, that's a good way to put it

7c561d95934ff0ee91ed658da29d6587: btw, the bugs I filed on HTML+RDFa can't cause backwards compat issues with processing existing content, because I didn't ask for processing model changes

b/c issues would relate to document conformance between XHTML1+RDFa and XHTML5+RDFa documents... so, you're right - there would be no b/c issues w/ the processing algorithm... but there would be b/c issues between XHTML1+RDFa and XHTML5+RDFa... (primarily because authors won't understand the nuanced difference between the two and would expect their XHTML1+RDFa documents to continue to "conform" under XHTML5+RDFa. I think we could make a technical argument that XHTML1+RDFa can be different from XHTML5+RDFa (based on document conformance)... but that nuance will be lost on authors, I imagine. The technical argument would go something like this: Since RDFa was never defined for XHTML5+RDFa, there are no backwards incompatible issues by not allowing @href on all elements. (but then, as I said a few hours ago, conformance differences for @href/@rel/@rev between XHTML1+RDFa and HTML5+RDFa will confuse authors) (leading me to the conclusion that we should not allow those attributes as conforming in RDFa Lite 1.1, and warn strongly against using @href/@rel/@rev on elements that traditionally didn't allow those attributes in RDFa 1.1 Full via validator warnings) ... understanding, of course, that the solution isn't acceptable to you. :)

021b07974a619a6b39ed3cd72e4b1972: IIRC: No. The only SQLite stuff HTML 5 does is to internet databases with access rights limited to the site that created it. s/internet/internal/ 021b07974a619a6b39ed3cd72e4b1972: That's an implementation detail. If it is implemented that way, then the user could shut down their browser, overwrite the file with a different one, then fire their browser up again. A website couldn't. A website could provide some data expressed in (for example) JSON that some JavaScript could use to create and populate a client side database. wow, f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, you're right, XHTML5 *is* a widely used term... about 1/10th as widely used as XHTML2 then why did you make the argument? the only reason I see for HTML5's XML serialization to be called XHTML (as far as I can tell) is to attempt to undermine the efforts of XHTML2 why isn't HTML5/XML just as good, for example? f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, I can read, and I've read that argument about 20 times now it's clear that that's your opinion, but remember, "opinions don't matter", right? I'm not debating, I'm pointing out that you aren't making very good arguments I have no investment in XHTML2 at all, myself on a syntactic level, perhaps but not in spirit ok, then why are you getting in a pissing contest about the name? if XHTML2 is so doomed, why would you even want XHTML5 to be associated with the name? or, in other news, why not just play nice and use a different name? I believe that the discussion was started by the WHATWG appropriating the W3C name XHTML, don't you agree? or am I mischaracterizing the situation? that wasn't my question, 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884 how is it a mischaracterization? f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220 stated that the term XHTML5 has been used for 3 years.... either it has been or it hasn't and, in fact, it has you should run for office :) I think they were chartered to work on the XHTML spec, right? I think it's not a very friendly way to start the discussion by appropriating the name of a language that they were chartered to define you can spin it howver you like, maciej, but I'll say again, the only reason I can see for the HTML WG (and the WHATWG) to use the term XHTML5 is to sow confusion and undermine the XHTML2 WG and I suspect you think the same thing you know it wouldn't, and you know why there's an easy way to do that: stop stepping on their toes... there are plenty of perfectly good acronyms out there but like I said, I'm just a spectator here ah, yes, "evidence" that's starting to sound like a dirty word define evidence, please... and do avoid using the word "evident" because it's clear that's not what you mean 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884, because there would be a name clash through iterations either way (assuming either language survives more than a couple decades, which I personally doubt) lol I honestly think you're a good guy, 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884, but I don't think you're being straightforward here f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, I've been at a meeting where there was, in fact, great confusion about the relationship of XHTML2 and XHTML5 it was a large meeting of mostly technical people

b65a1668d3f56352ebf6e4735afeb424: I wasn't making a comparison of how widely each are used, it makes no difference that "XHTML2" is used more than "XHTML5" because it is a widely used term.  just because A is more widely used than B, doesn't mean B isn't widely used so you're ignoring the fact that XHTML5 is much close to XHTML1, than XHTML2 is.  If only one is to retain the name, it should be the one that is closer to XHTML1. however, I couldn't care less if XHTML2 retains it's name.  XHTML2 is irrelevant well, then why are you still debating? that XHTML2 is irrelevant is my opinion, but that XHTML5 is closer to XHTML1 than XHTML2 is, is a fact (which I already supplied evidence for) there has been no real evidence for such confusion presented yet evidence for confusion would be things like forum posts, emails, blog posts, etc. that ask questions like what's the difference between XHTML2 and XHTML5, and saying I don't understand something, where such statements arise from the similarity in names

XHTML2's effort doesn't need any undermining they seem to be handling that fine by themselves I think it's fine for both to keep their current name I'm not the one who started asking the other group to change I think both using the XHTML1 namespace URI is a bigger problem, but it would be a problem for XHTML2 even if XHTML5 didn't exist - the normal name so far for an XML version of HTML has been XHTML, there doesn't seem to be any deep need to change it - why doesn't XHTML2 WG play nice and use a different name? (not that I care if they do, but they are the ones who seem to think different names are important) I think the XHTML2 WG passing a resolution that the HTML WG should not use a particular name is not a very friendly way to start the discussion WHATWG used the name "Web Apps 1.0" although unofficially people referred to it as HTML5 and XHTML5 now it is a W3C spec maintained by the HTML WG which has officially resolved to name it HTML5, but has not picked an official name for the XHTML serialization although popular and sensible proposals include XHTML 5 and XHTML 1.5 I think it's a mischaracterization to say "the discussion was started by the WHATWG appropriating the W3C name XHTML" which was in fact your question WHATWG didn't name anything XHTML5, random people called it that, now the WG is considering making it official no one told XHTML2 WG what they should or shouldn't name their spec both groups will be defining languages evolved from XHTML 1 I am sure arguments could be made why one side has more right to the name than the other I think sharing is just fine they are chartered to "continue the XHTML2 work" I didn't know they were chartered to define XHTML5 I don't think it says that in their charter I don't see a problem with both languages being named XHTML N for different values of N I'd be fine with XHTML 1.5 as a name if it made people happy (makes it more clear that it is related to the XHTML 1.x family of languages, not XHTML2) but I don't think it would make people happy I personally don't care what the XHTML2 WG does and I wish they would leave us alone we don't go to their mailing list to start turf wars or pissing matches it could certainly reduce confusion if they didn't use "H", "T", "M" and "L" in that order in their name since it may lead people to think their language is suitable for use as an on-the-wire format, or would work in browsers but I don't think it's a big problem for them to keep the XHTML2 name I actually don't know why XHTML 1.5 would be unacceptable either - it lets XHTML2 keep the privilege of the larger number and the appearance of the more radically forward-looking language I mean, I guess it is ok for the XHTML2 WG to make a polite request to change the name of the XML serialization of our language, but I also think it is ok for us to say "no" to that arguments could be made both ways why one has more or less right to claim their language is a successor to XHTML but arguing such things is a waste of time let's just be nice and share sample argument: XHTML5 will likely get served as application/xhtml+xml on the public web as a final format, XHTML2 likely won't (unless carefully restricted to an XHTML5 or XHTML1-compatible subset, or using trickery like client-side XSLT to transform to an actual end delivery format) seems like the thing that will be served with the XHTML MIME type should be named XHTML (this is not to disparage the potential value of XHTML2 as a back-end authoring format) you can see how arguments along these lines could easily turn into a mean-spirited dick size flamewar
